div.div: There may be alignments in the directions across multiple vector spaces

Depending on the definition of direction & the position of vectors, this may indicate similarity in intent (if multiple intents defined this way align, they may be interchangeable, similar, or composable if adjacent intent networks are semantically related).

There are patterns in intent types: if multiple intents in a stack or chain are neutral, that signals a malicious intent, when the sum or combination of the intents are graphed on the intent network space to indicate intent type.
Since intents can have multiple sub-intents from multiple perspective filters, each vector can map to another space where its stack or network of sub-intents is depicted.

div.span: Matching an intent with the proof (side effects, output) associated with that intent is one way to validate navigation permissions as a backup to governing system access.

For example, if a process claims that its intent is to retrieve information to resolve an info imbalance, they should have proof that they have the info imbalance, which means not only missing that info but also occupying a position on an intent chain that would create that info imbalance (proof of prior causes of info imbalances).

div.div: Similar function intents are adjacent, and buildable intents are external to initial intents.
There are ways to generate intents from non-standard intent paths, but there would have to be no filters in place to prevent alternate paths.

If you want to predict/test something, you'd start from the derive intent, and the changes to the resources you start with will indicate that you got to the target intents like predict from the standard/supported intent path.
If an intent like 'merge' or its side effects is presented to the 'predict' intent, it'll know that it's not supposed to execute that process.

Processes can be chained but if they need an intent on another path, rather than creating a path, they would return their output to the initiating process with a call to the next intent path required to get to the next target intent.
This system is hackable due to the cross-system applicability & generative nature of these functions (build can be used to generate find intents, derive can be used to generate change intents, etc).

For example, predict intents can be generated from the derive initial function (find the path from source to target to predict target from source) or the find initial function (find the curve fitting this data set).

Once you get more specific, some intents will only be applicable to unique or different paths, and you can inject requirements like requiring that every intent path hit one of the nodes that has unique impacts to provide proof of its trajectory to later/more guarded intents. Corresponding specific intents of a traditional computer would include calculate, execute, retrieve, store (with sub-intents like temporary store, private store, distributed store), compress, validate, equate, etc.

These intents can occupy a sub-intent network that is executed for machine intents, which is validated with more abstract intent networks, checking that the corresponding abstract intent path produces the same output target node from the same source. For example, the 'retrieve' intent aligns with the abstract 'find' intent, so their paths should match up if they are optimally implemented, except for where their definitions diverge.
You can also integrate other interfaces to this system - so a process would only be executed only if it complied with intent path rules, type path rules, etc.

Then you'd identify the similarities between outputs (intent paths generating similar side effects) to identify intent paths that can mimic another, and ways to differentiate them (like previously mentioned unique path node requirement or other intent path proof methods).

div.b: Application of Intent as a Function Prediction tool for a System Intent

div.div: It's possible to predict the correct core objects/functions, function layers, and function intersections to implement a system intent (such as building an app) optimally, given function intent metadata & change patterns/requirements.
Given that a system intent like building a nutrition calculation app has:
- change requirements: flexible function input types/sets
- core functions that can build all other functions: identify unique object, define object, differentiate object, fit object to structure, fit functions to intent
- neutral granular functions that can build higher-level functions: formatting functions, filtering functions
- interim functions to convert one function layer to another: classify, identify metric, approximate, predict (on app objects like portion, content, nutrients)

- information intent functions: fit info into app object/supported types, merge info according to probable system de-duplication rules (two immediate tests of nutrient content of a photo aren't likely to be fundamentally different content unless the location is a restaurant/store)
- dev intent functions: get data, validate data, build service, fit UI to user intents & data services, predict nutrient content, create prediction model
- user/app intent functions: get nutrient prediction of content in image
- emerging intent functions: update metrics automatically, update prediction model automatically, create prediction model automatically
The emerging functions may not be used by the system but they emerge from combinations of the explicitly built functions as possible functionality given the explicit function set.
